Author-Name:    Baxter, Marianne
Title:   Fiscal Policy, Specialization, and Trade in the Two-Sector Model: The Return of Ricardo? 
Journal: Journal of Political Economy
Pages: 713-44
Issue: 4
Volume: 100
Year: 1992
Month:  August 
Abstract:
  This paper develops a two-sector neoclassical model of international
 trade with endogenous capital accumulation and intertemporal optimization.
 In contrast to the traditional "2 x 2" model, there is a Ricardian
 implication that countries specialize according to comparative advantage.
 Consequently, the theory predicts that government expenditure policies are
 unlikely to affect the established pattern of specialization and trade,
 but that changes in tax policies can result in a dramatic reorganization
 of world production. Further, the dynamic 2 x 2 x 2 model can explain many
 of the salient features of international trade that are problematic for
 the standard Heckscher-Ohlin-Samuelson model.  Copyright 1992 by University of Chicago Press.
