Author-Name:    Kandel, Eugene
Author-Name:  Lazear, Edward P
Title:   Peer Pressure and Partnerships. 
Journal: Journal of Political Economy
Pages: 801-17
Issue: 4
Volume: 100
Year: 1992
Month:  August 
Abstract:
  Partnerships and profit sharing are often claimed to motivate workers by
 giving them a share of the pie. But in organizations of any significant
 size, the free-rider effects would seem to choke off any motivational
 forces. This analysis explores how peer pressure operates and how factors
 such as profit sharing, shame, guilt, norms, mutual monitoring, and
 empathy interact to create incentives in the firm. The argument that
 Japanese firms enjoy team spirit because compensation is linked to overall
 profitability is analyzed. An explanation for the prevalence of
 partnerships among individuals in similar occupations is provided.  Copyright 1992 by University of Chicago Press.
